When you arrive, you will undergo a quick temperature and health screening, then you‚Äôll be able to get your schedule and breakfast in the middle school gym and go directly to your first period class for homeroom. 1) ASAA has moved Wrestling season to begin Nov. 2nd and end Jan 30th at their board meeting yesterday.
2) We will have a volleyball parent meeting on Sept. 9th at 5:30 PM for interested HS girls. We will discuss the volleyball teams' mitigation plan, team contracts and work on completing any paperwork! All interested HS girls are welcome.
3) REMINDER on Sept 7th from 10 AM - 2 PM you can go to Arctic Chiropractic and get a free physical! :) No appointment necessary! Cassie MacDonald will be there and you can turn her physical in to her right afterwards so she can upload it into PlanetHS!

***In order to participate in any sport, all athletes must have their paperwork completed, including their COVID-19 waiver***

Just a reminder to stay safe during and try to stay physically distanced from others, wash your hands and take care of yourself! Have a beautiful weekend!

2020-2021 District Enrollment Now Open

Dear Parents and Guardians,

We are pleased to notify you that the 2020-2021 enrollment portal is now open on the district website. In order to provide the utmost of safety for your student(s) this year, student(s) must enroll prior to entering the building so that we have parent/guardian contact information available, can build our transportation schedule in a manner that minimizes the passenger load on each bus as well as to develop schedules which reduce class sizes to the maximum extent possible. Please spread the word and note that the enrollment period will close at 11:59 P.M. on August 31st, 2020. If you would like support with enrollment, please contact Ani (Elementary School at 842-5642) or Rachel (Middle/High School at 842-5221) and they‚Äôll happily help you along the way.

post_text:
Congratulations to the 2020 Senior Class!

We would just like to confirm that the graduation speeches will begin on KDLG at 6:00pm. The graduates will start driving the parade route 15 minutes after the speeches have finished broadcasting.

The route will start at the High School. The graduates will then drive from the school, past the Post Office, and up to the intersection by the senior center and youth center. From that intersection, the seniors will turn right and drive past the Togiak Wildlife Refuge building and past the Bristol Inn. At the next stop sign, they will drive turn left and pass n&n and then merge onto Kanakanak Rd. The graduates will turn around at the airport Y, and make their way back to the school for pictures.

The Locker rooms have been cleared!

Sorry for the delay but the homework packs had taken priority. We understand many of the students do not know the exact locker number that they had used this year, so attached is a diagram of the locker room layout, highlighting which lockers had items in it. Please ask your student the following questions before calling or emailing the school so that we can make sure everyone gets reunited with their gym items.

- Is your locker highlighted in the picture? If so which one?
- If you cant remember, what is the general area?
- What was in the locker?
- Please describe the shoes/contents of the locker. (Size, Color, Brand, etc.)

Please email rtilden@dlgsd.org with this information along with your students name and a good phone number to call you at to discuss a pickup.

Thanks again for your patience!

post_text:
See the following message from Superintendent Johnson:

Dear Wolverine Fitness Center Members,

First, we hope that this message finds each of you well and seeking different methods to keep up with your active lifestyles and pursuits!

Next, please know that all gym memberships will be extended by an equal amount of months that were impacted due to COVID-19. For example, if the gym is shut down for three months an additional three months will be added to your membership at no cost.

Moving forward, we will continue to keep an eye on other mandates and health updates throughout the state and will reach back out once we believe it is safe for
the fitness center to be fully active once again. In short, with the extremely small space, social-distancing and other precautionary measures are difficult to adhere to.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to reach out to Mr. Phil Hulett (Our Business Manager at 907-842-6711).

Sincerely,

Jason

As COVID-19 continues to impact us all, here are some resources for parents/guardians to learn more about the Coronavirus Disease 2019.

The first resource is a link to the Alaska Department of Education and Early Development website which is a great source for information as it develops in Alaska:

https://education.alaska.gov/safeschools/infectiousdisease

The second link is guidance for parents/guardians trying to talk to children about COVID-19:

https://store.samhsa.gov/product/Talking-With-Children-Tips-for-Caregivers-Parents-and-Teachers-During-Infectious-Disease-Outbreaks/PEP20-01-01-006

As you talk to children, please remind them to practice social distancing outside the house by staying a snow machine‚Äôs length away from other people (6 feet).

By putting safety first and sharing knowledge, we protect each other!

post_text: Hello DMHS Community! The middle school is putting on Exploratory Week from March 9th-11th, right before spring break. Throughout Exploratory Week, middle school students will participate in a variety of sessions and activities relevant to their current and future lives. We are looking for community members that are interested in volunteering as chaperones during Exploratory Week. Chaperones would accompany a teacher and group of 15-20 students as they rotate between sessions. If you are interested in volunteering for a full day or even a morning or afternoon, please contact Megan Green by calling the school or sending an email to mgreen@dlgsd.org. We appreciate you!

post_text:
Dear Parents, Guardians and Community Members,

Currently, we have students and staff members participating in a basketball tournament in Manokotak.

Please know that there is a situation which is contained and occurring roughly five miles from the school and that the school staff, local VPSOs and community members have done a tremendous job of keeping things under control as well as everyone safe and that they anticipate the state police to arrive shortly.

The students, staff and participants are safe and are not in any danger and the school is being monitored as an additional precaution.

Cell phone coverage is extremely limited in the building. Therefore, you will likely not be able to contact your students or members traveling with the team at the current time.

Should any additional information arise, we will pass that along as quickly as it becomes known to us as we are in on-going contact with SWRSD staff.

Sincerely,

Jason Johnson
Superintendent
Dillingham City School District

Lindsay Layland‚ÄéDillingham HS Wolverine Fan Club
January 11 at 11:35 PM ¬∑

BETHEL VFW TOURNAMENT RECAP:

Congratulations to the DLG Lady Wolverines on securing the tournament championship! After battling 3 tough games against YK Region teams, the Wolverines overtook Toksook Bay in the final game, 47-31

Kiley Clouse and Twig Bavilla led the team in championship game scoring with 15 and 14 points, respectively, and both got a double-double!!

Big shout-outs to Senior Abbey Whitcomb, who led the team to three victories and earned All-Tournament Team Honors!

But that's not all... Huge kudos to Senior Reagan Finkenbinder, who earned TOURNAMENT MVP!!

And...the girls did it all on Cadence Dray's 15th Birthday!

Congrats to the Boys Team who finished the tourney 2-1! Sophomore Sam Fox also made the boys all tourney team!

**Teams are expected to leave Bethel at 12pm for return flight to DLG.

October 23, 2019 at 8:15 AM ¬∑

DCSD Elementary School is Proud to Bring You - Team Hollywood Superhero Basketball!

When: Friday, October 25th from 6:00 - 7:30 P.M.

Please join us on Friday night in the Elementary School Gym for a fun-filled and memorable evening as our students will learn important skills about friendship, building positive relationships and treating each other with respect from Action Heroes!

Team Hollywood is an inspirational, funny and exciting group of former stars, athletes and all-around great people who travel across the country spreading joy, energy and life-lessons with students.

We look forward to seeing you and your children here for an extremely exciting evening.

Sincerely,

DCSD Staff

Hello DMHS Community,

We are getting very excited for the school year to start and we hope that you are too! There are several staffing changes at the middle/high school this year, including the whole main office:

Principal: Vincent Kane
Director of School Climate and Culture: Eston Jennings
Counselor: Alex Ting
Secretary: Rachel Tilden

Alex, Eston, and I will be camped out in the entrance of the AC store on August 13th from 4:30-6:00 PM to say hello and pass out some school materials to students and families that stop by. If you‚Äôre not able to visit with us, no worries! We‚Äôll get the materials to you another way.

Enjoy the rest of the summer!

-Vincent

DCSD and BBNA are partnering to host Child Find on March 28th and 29th at the BBNA Family Resource Center.

Child Find is a free developmental screening process for any child who was 3 or older by September 1, 2018. The screening looks at several developmental areas and helps to determine if a student needs additional support services.
